ative choice."}, "identify_pain": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["Avoma discovery call 2026-06-16, Maribel Giraldo (pain owner)", "SF Customer_Business_Problem__c not populated", "SF Pain_points_in_the_current_solution__c not populated"], "narrative": "Partial pain confirmed, but not owned by a senior leader. On the 2026-06-16 discovery call, Maribel Giraldo (Director of Procurement Services) described three operational pain points: (1) siloed procurement operations across Touro's multi-campus structure ('We are just very big and still operating in silos'), (2) low adoption of Unimarket's CLM module despite demos ('We've done demos for the contract module, but no traction yet'), and (3) lack of visibility into what procurement tools are available in the market ('I always want to make sure I know what's available'). These are real qualitative pains tied to decentralization and underutilized technology, but Maribel did not quantify the cost (e.g. dollars lost to maverick spend, hours wasted on manual intake, contract leakage). She also framed her exploration as proactive market research, not a crisis: Unimarket 'serves a purpose.' The pain is acknowledged but not acute, and it is owned by a mid-level procurement director, not a CFO, Provost, or VP of Operations who would sponsor a platform replacement. Without a senior pain-owner and a quantified case, this pain will not drive a decision. The move is to ask Maribel to introduce Justin to the finance or operations leader who feels the cost of siloed procurement most acutely, and to quantify the pain with her: 'What does fragmented procurement cost Touro annually in time, compliance risk, or spend leakage?'"}, "paper_process": {"status": "gap", "sources": ["SF Mandate__c not populated", "SF Current_Contract_Expiration__c not populated", "Avoma discovery call 2026-06-16 (no contracting discussion)"], "narrative": "Paper process is unknown. There is no evidence of contracting mechanics (MSA/SOW, legal review, procureme